## Problem 1: Received Power

> Find the received power at the destination when the sender is transmitting information with a power of **1 mW**. The antenna gains at transmitter and receiver are **$G_t = 5$** and **$G_r = 10$**, respectively. The distance between the transmitter and the receiver is **1 km** and the frequency at which the transmitter is operating is **2.4 GHz**.
>
> *(Hint: take care of the units)*

---

**Step 1: Convert to dB**

| Value | Calculation | Result |
|-------|-------------|--------|
| $P_t = 1$ mW | $10\log_{10}(1)$ | **0 dBm** |
| $G_t = 5$ | $10\log_{10}(5)$ | **7 dB** |
| $G_r = 10$ | $10\log_{10}(10)$ | **10 dB** |

---

**Step 2: Calculate path loss**

Using FSPL: $L_p = 20\log_{10}\left(\frac{4\pi d f}{c}\right)$

$$L_p = 20\log_{10}\left(\frac{4\pi \times 1000 \times 2.4 \times 10^9}{3 \times 10^8}\right)$$

$$L_p = 20\log_{10}(100531) \approx 100 \text{ dB}$$

---

**Step 3: Apply Friis equation**

$$P_r = P_t + G_t + G_r - L_p$$

$$P_r = 0 + 7 + 10 - 100 = -83 \text{ dBm}$$

> **Answer:** The received power is **-83 dBm**.

---

## Problem 2: dBm to Watts

> Assume that the 5G received power is **$P_r = -72$ dBm**. What will be the received power in Watts?

---

**The formula:**

$$P_{\text{watts}} = 10^{(P_{\text{dBm}} - 30) / 10}$$

---

**Substitute:**

$$P = 10^{(-72 - 30) / 10} = 10^{-102/10} = 10^{-10.2}$$

$$P \approx 6.31 \times 10^{-11} \text{ W}$$

> **Answer:** **63 picowatts** (or $6.31 \times 10^{-11}$ W).

