## Problem 3: Path Loss and Eb/No

> Calculate the **path loss ($L_{dB}$)** and the **$E_b/N_0$** of a WiFi system.
>
> **Given:**
> - $h_t = 0.5$ m
> - $h_r = 1$ m
> - $d = 100$ m *(assumed - some exam papers omit this value)*
> - 8 kbits/sample at 1000 samples/sec
> - $k$ = Boltzmann's constant = $1.3803 \times 10^{-23}$ J/K
> - BW = 30 MHz
> - T = 300 K

**Note:** Past exam papers sometimes omit the distance. If this happens, state your assumption (e.g., "assuming d = 100m for indoor WiFi") and proceed with the calculation.

---

### Part A: Path Loss

Since antenna heights are given, use the **two-ray ground model**:

$$L_p = 40\log_{10}(d) - 20\log_{10}(h_t) - 20\log_{10}(h_r)$$

---

**Calculate each term:**

| Term | Calculation | Result |
|------|-------------|--------|
| $40\log_{10}(100)$ | $40 \times 2$ | **80 dB** |
| $20\log_{10}(0.5)$ | $20 \times (-0.301)$ | **-6 dB** |
| $20\log_{10}(1)$ | $20 \times 0$ | **0 dB** |

---

**Combine:**

$$L_p = 80 - (-6) - 0 = 86 \text{ dB}$$

> **Path loss:** **86 dB**

---

### Part B: Eb/No

**Step 1: Calculate data rate**

$$R_b = 8 \text{ kbits/sample} \times 1000 \text{ samples/sec} = 8{,}000{,}000 \text{ bps} = 8 \text{ Mbps}$$

---

**Step 2: Use the Eb/No formula**

Assuming transmit power $P_t = 20$ dBm (100 mW, typical WiFi):

$$P_r = P_t - L_p = 20 - 86 = -66 \text{ dBm}$$

The formula (at T = 300K):

$$\frac{E_b}{N_0} = P_r\text{(dBm)} - 10\log_{10}(R_b) + 173.8$$

---

**Step 3: Calculate**

$$\frac{E_b}{N_0} = -66 - 10\log_{10}(8 \times 10^6) + 173.8$$

$$\frac{E_b}{N_0} = -66 - 69 + 173.8 = 38.8 \text{ dB}$$

> **Eb/No:** **38.8 dB** (excellent - systems typically need 10-20 dB)

---

